{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"5fe2ec7e-2e62-446e-a9c5-ffdaa2cb8124","content":"Use `dotnet-trace` — it's the lightest option for containers:\n\n```bash\n# Install the tool inside the pod\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# Find your app's PID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect a CPU profile (30s example)\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can copy out and open in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or convert to **Speedscope**:\n\n```bash\n# Convert for Speedscope (browser-based viewer)\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format speedscope\n\n# Copy out of the pod\nkubectl cp <pod>:/path/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**Tips:**\n- If `dotnet tool` isn't available, download the standalone `dotnet-trace` from the [diagnostics repo releases](https://github.com/dotnet/diagnostics).\n- For production, consider `--buffersize 512` to reduce overhead.\n- If you need OS-level detail (native frames, kernel), use `dotnet-trace collect --format speedscope -p <PID> -- --clrevents gc+jit` or fall back to **`perf`** with `/tmp/perf-<pid>.map` JIT maps (`export DOTNET_PerfMapEnabled=1`).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b5042db1-e927-485b-9a6c-dca95446824e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a diagnostic/troubleshooting question, not a code change task. I'll provide concise, practical advice.","outputTokens":408,"requestId":"6415:32055B:DE38401:F7A5421:69EC155C"},"id":"2856a740-f28b-401f-9e64-9a2b909827b7","timestamp":"2026-04-25T01:14:14.792Z","parentId":"cbd58926-bd41-4d7e-9c90-9f004c7b9a5b"}
